column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: At about 0900 The Brewster Yard crew noticed leaking tank car CEWX 603 Vaporizing off from the protective housing.  This was a residue propane. The yardmaster called me, john Vergis Hazardous Materials/environmental Officer for the WLE, and I went to the car which was in 12 track and noticed a very heavy vapor coming from the car.  When I climbed on top the car and removed the seal, number 24990685, I found that both the liquid lines were frosted and leaking.  The vapor valve also was leaking.  I tried turning the valves to see if they were tight and they were not.  All three valves took at least ¼ turn.  The vapor valve stopped leaking but the two liquid lines did not.  I then tried to tighten the valve plugs to see if they were loose.  They were less than tool tight.  I tightened them and the leak slowed considerably but did not stop.  I did not want to take the plug out of the valve not knowing how much force was going to be behind them.  I called Chemtrec to make a report and for them to get in touch with the shipper.  The waybill was not even close to having the right information on it as it had a Canadian company listed as the emergency contact and when I called them, they were not able to help me.  The PUCO finally gave me a name to call in Florida from Amerigas which got the ball rolling to get the issue resolved.  During all this, I called Enviroserve, and emergency Response Contractor, which came out to look at the car and they confirmed what I had thought, the valves were defective and needed replaced.  With permission of the car owner, Enterprise Products out of Canada, Enviroserve came out at 1400 hrs. and started to flare the car down.  They then on 10-2-2020, came back out and replaced both liquid lines and then bubble leak tested the car with Nitrogen.   The car passed the bubble leak test and the car was returned into transportation. New seal # 2880491 was applied to the protective housing.
column169: Better procedures need followed when securing the car for transportation.

On October 5, 2020 at 1352 personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered TILX280736, a loaded tank car of  Isopropylbenzene with a vapor leak from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and Marathon Petroleum, Kentucky Division of Emergency Management and National Response Center were  notified CHEMTREC Report #2020100500192. Marion Environmental Inc., a CSXT response  contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a detectable vapor release coming from the  bottom outlet valve secondary securement cap. Upon further inspection it was found that the bottom outlet valve was leaking liquid from around the ball in the valve, causing the secondary securement  cap to fill with liquid. The gasket in the secondary securement cap was damaged allowing a vapor  release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael  Murray 606-921-6255. Contractor personnel changed the damaged gasket in the secondary  securement cap securing the vapor leak. The leaky bottom outlet valve was unable to be fixed in  the field.TILX280736 load was transferred into TILX280707 on-site. TILX280736 was completely  emptied and was moved on an OTMA back to the home shop for repairs.   2(5+1) x (2+0) = 24 Narri

At 0901 Hours on 10-9-2020, The Public Utilities Commission of Ohio had inspectors on the property doing a routine inspection of the Brewster rail yard when they noticed tank cat UTLX 950375 with a frosted Protective Housing and Vapor coming from it.  They called myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, to investigate.  When I arrived, I did notice the protective housing being frosted and vapor coming from the top.  I climbed on top the car and removed seal number 18160789 and opened the lid to find that the liquid valve on the B end was frosted over and leaking.  I tried to tighten the valve to see if the leak would stop and it didn't.  I was able to get a slight turn out of it but it still would not seal.  I checked to see if the plug was loose since that's where it was leaking from and it was less than tool tight.  I tightened the valve plug and the leak stopped.  I also noticed that the valve stem on the A end of the car was bent.  The valve was not leaking but needs replaced.  I called Enterprise Products in Canada who owns the car and we will be making arrangements with them to get the car repaired.  The car has been shopped at our Brewster car shop.

column168: At 0300 hrs. on 10-4-2020, the Rook Yard Switch Crew noticed tank car PROX 45002 leaking from the bottom outlet valve as they were switching the cut of cars.  The conductor called the Rook yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway.  I then called Specialized Professional Services out  of Washington, Pa to look at the car.  When they arrived, they noticed that the Disengaging Bottom Outlet Valve handle was in the closed position but the valve was leaking through the threads of the valve cap.  It was determined that the valve was defective and that the car needed to be transferred into another rail car which was done on 10-6-2020.  There was a Haz Hammock installed under the car to catch any product that may leak from the valve. The valve was also sealed with Pug -N- Dike and then absorbent wipes were put around the valve.  The car will be sent to Home Shop for repairs.

column168: The GATX 90725 was reported leaking by a CPUC Hazmat Inspector.  Upon inspection of the car, the top operated bottom outlet valve handle was open approximately one quarter of a turn, the quarter turn valve assembly on the bottom outlet cap was in the slightly open position and the bottom outlet plug was less than tool tight.  All valves were closed and the plug was secured to tool tight stopping the release.

Car was reported to have what appeared to be a steam cloud over in after being put in the bowl.  A Chlorep contractor was dispatched and upon investigation determined that there was approximately 5 gallons of product inside the housing but nothing was loose and no obvious signs of the leaks origin.  The car was decontaminated and moved to the 700 yard where the contractor  began pressuring the car with nitrogen and determined the release was from the fill hole.  The bolts were tight however upon opening it was determined that the fill hole gasket was misaligned.  The gasket was properly aligned and secured.  Nitrogen pressure was placed back on the car and monitored for 17 minutes with no further issues.  The car was returned to transportation.
column169: Ensure the car is properly secured and ready for transportation

column168: On 10/13/20, at 1100 hrs., HM Scott Karcher, a hazardous materials manager, in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered GATX 37410, a loaded tank car of elevated temperature, liquid, N.O.S, leaking from pressure relief device. The car was isolated and CHEMTREC and Afton Chemical were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2020-1001-00296. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device had actuated and product on the side of the railcar and prd. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Wayne Kennedy, 804-239-0332. Contractor personnel checked the pressure on the car, snooped the prd and remediated the released product. PRD is currently waiting to be replaced. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 will be required.

column168: On 10/15/20 at around 1041 hours EST personnel reported a confirmed hazmat release from tank car HOMX101238, residue Petroleum Gases, Liquefied, at MP 000707 in Pascagoula, MS.  The car was isolated and the consignee, Targa Transport C/O Chevron were contacted (Ed Davis 228-990-3983). column168: Driver was traveling down Hwy 64 near Tyler, TX.  This is a two lane road.  There was a car (2) slowing in the oncoming traffic lane waiting for traffic to clear so they could make a left turn.  Before 2 could execute the turn it was struck in the rear by another car (1) forcing car 2 into our truck's (3) lane of travel.  Our driver had very little time to react and hit car 2 head on with the left front 3.  This caused 3 to veer into a field to its right where it struck a tree with the tanker trailer causing a small rupture in the right front shoulder of the tanker.  Roughly 50 gallons of unleaded gas leaked.

column168: At 2100 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics to report a spill. The caller stated that .5 gallons of an unknown product were discovered on the dock released from a box. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup activities. Enviroserve arrived on site at 2210 ET. The spill impacted a 3' x 3' area on the dock. Envroserve confirmed the product released was "Euro Kwik Clearcoat". Three gallons released from (4)5 liter metal cans that were punctured by the forklift. At 2315 ET, Enviroserve was almost finished cleaning the impacted area when the floor manager came over and told them there was a second area of impact measuring 8 'x 5' on the dock. All waste was containerized into a 55 gallon metal drum which was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A sweet odor was reported in the yard.  Upon inspection this car was found to be releasing from the pressure relief device.  The valve was set at 75 psi and the car had 20 pounds on it.  A midland kit was applied to the car securing the release and the car was moved to an isolated track for further work.  The release could not be totally secured with the Midland kit so it was removed and the PRD taken apart where it was determined that the larger o-ring appeared to be degraded with almost half missing.  A new Viton-A o-ring was installed and the valve put back together.  A leak test with Snoop was performed and no leak present. column168: On October 23 at 1142 personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered TILX191089, a loaded tank car of Isopropyl benzene with a vapor leak from the bottom of the vapor valve. The car was isolated and  Marathon Petroleum, Kentucky Division of Emergency Management and National Response Center were notified CHEMTREC Report #2020102300170. Marion Environmental Inc., a CSXT response  contractor,was dispatched to the scene and found a detectable vapor release coming from the threaded  connection at the bottom end of the vapor valve. Upon further inspection it was found that the  bottom female threaded connection of the valve had threads that were stripped/missing allowing  the connection to leak. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the  shipper Michael Murray 606-921-6255. Contractor personnel changed the damaged valve out and  replace it with a suitable AAR spec valve. After the valve replacement, technician’s pressure tested  the vessel with nitrogen to verify that the new valve was not leaking.TILX191089 was moved on an  OTMA back to the home shop for repairs.   2(5+1) x (2+0) = 24 Narri Score

column168: On 10/24/20 at around 1730 hours EST personnel reported a confirmed hazmat release from tank car GATX22936, loaded Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. Hepaco was dispatched to the car and discovered an opening around the base of the valve assembly where it connects into the shell of the car to have severe corrosion causing an opening through the tank shell causing a release. The car was then cleaned and purged and will move under OMTA to a shop.    NAR Cause Code: 652- Tank shell crack  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI   Jacksonville, FL GATX22936, Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. column168: At 1715 EST, Dupre Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a tanker release. Yvonne stated an estimated 20 gallons of UN1203, Gasoline released to the underlying asphalt during unloading. The local FD is on scene and has requested an ETA to respond to the site for cleanup. Yvonne stated the cause of the release is unknown (mechanical or human error). ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who arrived on site and estimated that approximately 25 gallons released to from the tanker due to an overfill while the driver was off loading into a UST. The release is contained to the parking lot in a 20' x 25' area of asphalt. The contractor utilized granular absorbents, pads and hand tools to clean the impacted areas. All waste was collected, containerized, and taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: On 10/21/20 at approximately 1300 hours an IMTT Field Operator was in the process of setting up a transfer into tank # 7504 when he discovered oil in the pump containment.  The IMTT Field Operator immediately contacted his supervisor to report the incident.  The IMTT Operations Supervisor told the IMTT Field Operator to shut down the suction to those affected pumps.  ACV Enviro (IMTT's OSRO) was contacted and responded to the area to perform a cleanup operation.
column169: Upon investigation it was determined that a seal on Pump # 7 failed and caused the oil to leak out.  The concrete pump containment was also discovered to have cracks in several locations which allowed some the water/oil mix to seep out.  Pump # 7 has been removed from service for repairs.  The pump containment will be repaired by an IMTT approved contractor to prevent any further containment breaches.

column168: On October 14, 2020, at 1700 hours, Conrail was notified of a leaking tank car at the Bayway Yard, Elizabeth, New Jersey  reported by an FRA Hazardous Material Inspector who took exception to UTLX 677618, a loaded tank car of UN3256,  Elevated Temperature Liquid, Flammable, N.O.S. (Decanted Oil). Reportedly there was product around the manway and the  manway gasket was not properly sealed. The tank car was removed from the outbound train and isolated. The Consignee,  New York Terminals, was notified directly. Marion Environmental, a Conrail emergency response contractor, and Joe Caccamo Conrail Hazardous Material Manager were both dispatched to the Bayway Yard. Upon investigation it was found that the  manway had released product and the gasket was in shreds thus not allowing a proper seal against leakage. The shipper  representative International Chemical Co. who is the Freight Payer, Tracy Gallemore, 918-496-7711 was notified of the situation found and would contact their Shipper provider Midwest Terminals Toledo Intl. Once the gasket was  replaced and the tank car properly secured it was released back to transportation.   NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60 Cause code: 209

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver filled out our safe delivery form and donned his PPE.  He opened his external and internal valves allowing product to flow via gravity. The driver started applying air pressure from the front of the tanker and when he returned to the rear of the tanker he noticed drips (being captured by his bucket). He closed his internal and external valves, shut down the air pressure and reaffixed the hose to the customer fitting using a shim. He opened his external and internal valves again and confirmed there were no longer leaks. As the driver was returning to the front of the tanker to apply air, the safety pressure relief valve popped releasing spray in the customer's receiving garage and also down on our driver.  Our driver engaged the customer's safety shower for at least 15 minutes. He was contacted by sulfuric acid on the top of his ear and a small amount on his left cheek.  Tanker was very full as it is loaded on a slightly slanted loading rack.
column169: We are limiting how full we fill our tanker trucks to avoid overfilling them to avoid recurrence of this event.

column168: On October 9, 2020 at 1033 ET, Landstar Ranger experienced a 20 gallons release of UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide solution, 8, PGII "Neutrachill" from one (1) 275 - gallon tote when the valve became loose impacting the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot below the trailer. Hull's Environmental Services was dispatched out of Panama City, FL to perform cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival to the site, an 8' by 40' area of the trailer and concrete parking lot below were confirmed impacted by approximately 20 gallons of Neutrachill. The contractor applied granular absorbents to the impacted areas to absorb and solidify the released product. The spent absorbents were collected and containerized into five (5) 55 - gallon metal drums. Hull's Environmental Services personnel then departed the site with the waste generated.

column168: On 10/28/2020 during unloading activities at the terminal it was discovered that 1-275 poly tote was leaking. The leak was contained to the containment liner of the tote and no product reached the trailer floor or dock area.  The trailer was quarantined and a contractor was dispatched on 10/29/20 to transfer the damaged tote into a new poly tote and was sent onto the consignee. Once the damaged tote was transferred it was determined the the damaged tote leaked due to degradation to the bottom corner of the tote as the material was thin and flimsy compared to the other parts of the tote when the contractor cut the damaged tote up for pending disposal activities.

WITH THE PH COMING BACK SLIGHTLY ACIDIC I SPRINKLED SODIUM BICARBONATE ONTO THE SPILL. ONCE SPILL WAS CLEAN WITH SPEEDY DRY I TRANSPORTED CONTAINED SPILL AND PACKAGE TO DMP AREA FOR PROPER PROCESSING. ONCE PROPERLY SOLIDIFIED IN GREEN DMP BAG WITH ALL THE INFORMATION I NEEDED , I PROCESSED THIS CORROSIVE HAZMAT.

column168: Veolia employees were off-loading a trailer and placed the drums in the process area to review the load with the paperwork. They noticed a 5 gallon carboy which was bulging and in the process of them preparing to vent the drum, it ruptured at the bottom of the container.  The content of the carboy was hydrogen peroxide (8-25% peroxide) (40%) with methanol (60%). The container was half full so approximately 2.5 gallons spilled. The damage to the drum was about a two inch split on the bottom of the container.   The Veolia employees placed absorbent granules on the spill and placed absorbent pad over the storm drain.  The material was swept up and then the entire area was pressure washed which the rinse water was vacuumed up and containerized for disposal.
column169: Veolia EHS management reviewed the incident with the employees who packaged and shipped the material. A formal training was done on 10/27/2020 discussing the proper packaging requirements for materials that potentially may pressurize during transportation.  In addition, we have talked with the shipper regarding this material and ordered vented caps for these type of shipments.  In the future, Veolia employees will verify that these are in vented containers prior to pick up and shipment.

On October 27 at 1745 personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered SHPX210956, a empty tank car  of Isopropyl benzene with a vapor leak coming from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and  Advansix, Marathon Petroleum, Kentucky Division of Emergency Management and National Response  Center were notified CHEMTREC Report #2020-102700265. Quick Response, a CSXT response  contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a detectable vapor release coming from the  vacuum relief device (VRD). Upon further inspection it was found that O-ring gasket inside the VRD  was not sealing allowing vapor to escape the device. The issue identified and corrective actions  were communicated to the shipper Advansix, Larry Buffey 810-931-0280. Contractor personnel  removed the VRD and replaced it with a new VRD provided by Marathon Petroleum. The car was secured and was moved on an OTMA back to the home shop for repairs.   2(4+1) x (2+0) = 20 Narri

Local police, fire, and EMS responded to the incident and ordered an initial evacuation of the area. column168: On 10/25/20, RDWY 261218 was found to be leaking upon deramp at the San Bernardino IMF.  In the interest of Safety, the unit was placed into the containment area to be inspected.  On behalf of the shipper, Hazmat One was contacted and subsequently Ocean Blue was dispatched to complete inspection/remediation.  The contractor completed inspection/remediation at 02:30 10/26/20.  Interior inspection revealed palletized mixed freight varying in size and weight stowed 2 high throughout.  Unapproved use of a loadbbar was utilized as doorway securement with no signs of any lateral securement used within the load.  The source of the leak was found to originate in the middle of the unit.  The spilled product was determined to be Seagate Paint Coating (Synpex Flat White) carrying a Flammable marker UN 1263 in 5 gallon pails.  The cause of the spill was determined to be a result of the failed packaging due to the weight being applied from the second layer of palletized freight resulting in 2 pales to crush losing approximately 8 quarts of product.
column169: Shipper should ensure that adequate blocking and bracing are in place to prevent shifting of the load during transport.  Additionally, care should be taken to prevent stacking of materials which could crush lower containers.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en-route from the shipper’s  location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made  a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load  quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation,  it was discovered that approximately 8 ounces of material had escaped from the valve on the  container.  Driver immediately identified the leak and put spill containment down. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to transfer liquid from damaged tote into new tote.  Additionally, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate were collected  and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto  the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was  observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced  structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked  to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

IV Driver was ask to back to dock with his doors open. He was told to remain in the vehicle.  After the unload the driver was rushed by the shipper to pull forward and shut only one door. He was instructed the guard at out bound would inspect and verify the trailer was empty, the trailer close the door, and give hime the signed paperwork.  The guard ask the driver to come to the rear of the trailer to show him there had been a spill in his trailer but he would not be allowed to stay on their property to handle the situation. There was no release to the ground. Which liquid had spilled in the trailer was unknown and unavailable.   The driver then called and found a Wash out facility (Four Seasons truck wash in Hutchens Texas who agreed to wash the trailer out.   After the driver completed the washout the smell of the corrosive was strong so the driver called Safety reported the incident and Safety had the driver return the trailer to Memphis, Tn to the lease shop for additonal inspection.

column168: At 11:00AM our driver was traveling WB on interstate 80 in lane 4 approaching the Hilltop Rd onramp when he saw a motorcyclist merging onto the freeway.  The motorcyclist lost control and the motorcycle continued to travel onto the freeway headed straight in front of our truck.   Our driver was unable to maneuver to his left due to a car occupying that lane and was unable to maneuver to the right without overturning the truck.  Out truck struck the motorcycle.  Upon impact, he immediately saw flames that completely blocked his view but as he pulled over the flames began to subside.  Once stopped, our driver exited the vehicle and could see the bike lodged under his vehicle.  He gave it a couple pulls to see if he could dislodge it but was unable.  Our driver dialed 911 as the flames started to grow from the lodged motorcycle.   He decided it was not safe to stay with the vehicle and started walking away from the truck.  Once the fire department arrived the entire cab of the truck was engulfed in flames.  The truck cargo tank was breached at the top due to the heat of the fire. The fire department continued to spray water on it for about 2 hours until the flames subsided. Multiple agencies responded to the incident and will have more information as they become available.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s  location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the  purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued  transportation.  During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 8 ounces of material had escaped from a crack  that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a  response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were  collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was  placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was  observed. column168: Driver arrived in Indianapolis, he was to unload the box at Heritage Transport, LLC to await treatment at the plant facility. As the driver was unloading the box from his truck, liquid escaped through the top of the roll-off box and the tarp that was secured to it to prevent pieces of dry product from flying out during transit. Approximately 10 or so gallons of liquid spilled from the box onto the blacktop. No drains, grass, soil, or waterways were affected by the spill. Everything was contained on the blacktop within Heritage property.  The spill was reported about 1:15 pm and an in-house Heritage Field Services crew were immediately dispatched to come and clean up the spill.  Both the onsite waste coordinator at U.S. Steel and driver failed to check the inside of the box for free liquids (which are not allowed).  This is the responsibility of both the onsite waste coordinator, who is responsible for ensuring that the waste containers are acceptable for transport, and the driver (driver should always check their load before transport). This liquid was most likely caused by rain getting through an unsecured corner of the cover tarp. Had either checked the container for liquid before transport, this incident would never have happened.
column169: The onsite waste coordinator and the driver will both be counseled in addition to undergoing retraining on thoroughly inspecting both the outside and the inside of the boxes before shipment. There is also a checklist on the Stop Ticket that includes inspecting all roll-offs for liquids.  All affected Heritage employees will complete refresher training on the use of this checklist.

column168: The shipper informed the courier that the package contained epoxy. Since the courier was not certain it should have been offered as nonhazardous the employee brought it to a DG specialist back at the origin location. The package was opened. Inside the outer box were three inner boxes. One of those inner boxes exhibited the Limited Quantity Ground mark and contained ten containers of epoxy each 330 mL/465 g. The epoxy had Globally Harmonized System(GHS) labels with the corrosive symbol, the environmentally hazardous symbol. The manufacturer's name was Hilta and their product name was HlLTI- HIT RE 500 V3. A google search for this specific manufacturer's product yielded an SDS that classified the shipment for IATA/ICAO as UN 3259, Amines solid, corrosive n.o.s. a Class 8 corrosive. As the shipment had not been offered by the shipper with any DG markings, DG labels nor a shipper's declaration it's undeclared DG. The FAA was notified via email and photos were sent. This shipment was discovered at the origin location.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On October 9,2020, at approximately 2:00 pm CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (RLC) was making a delivery at the above-referenced location when the driver observed five(5) 50-pound bags of sodium nitrite powder(UN1500) punctured due to an unknown cause. As a result of the puncture, approximately one(1) pound of UN1500 was released to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LLC(FCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. Crews placed the five(5) 50-pound punctured bags of UN1500 into one(1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. FCE personnel then utilized a HEPA filter shop-vacuum to collect the UN1500 from the impacted surface. All UN1500 impacted material was collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. Crews transported the drum to the R+L terminal in Burlington, NJ until an approved profile could be completed. FCE personnel scheduled to return to the R+L terminal at a later date to pick up the generated waste.

column14: ON I59 NORTHBOUND AT THE I-59
column25: HONEYWELL INTERNATIONAL CARE OF PALMER LOGISTICS
column168: According to the information the following occured. While in transit, the AN Enterprises wasinvolved in a single-vehicle , rollover accident. As a result of the accident, the freight being carried by the vehicle was damaged, resulting in the release of approximately 2500 gallons of UN2922, Corrosive Liquid, Toxic , NOS to the roadway and soils adjacent to the roadway. The Fire Department responded to the site and deployed absorbent materials to contain the free product. The alabama Department of Environmental Management responded to the site I-59 Northbound at the I-59 and I-65 Split was closed as a result of the accident. Well Wrecker responded to the Site. I-59 Northbound at the I-59 and split was closed as a result of the accident. Weil Wrecker responded to the assist with vehicle recovery and spill cleanup. Miller Environmental was retained by AN Enterprises, Inc. to assist with vehicle recovery and spill cleanup. Miller Environmental was retained by AN Enterprises, Inc. to assist with spill cleanup and remediation of impacted soils, Telephonic regulatory reports were submitted to the National Response Center, the Alabama Department of Environmental Management, and the Jefferson County LEPC. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Driver had loaded in Pace, FL with a destination of Webster City, IA. Driver had stopped in Birmingham, AL. He had done a walk around(Circle of Safety) of his tractor and trailer and noticed nothing was happening at this time. He then drove to exit 322 off 65 north in Falkville, AL and stops at a truck stop at this exit. Once parked, driver gets out and does another walk around(Circle of Safety) when he notices product releasing from the pressure relief valve (PRV) from the top at the rear of the trailer. The driver immediately calls our Central Dispatch office to report the incident. Dispatch got the Terminal Manager& Safety on the call with the driver. Driver was instructed to call 911 and get immediate assistance to the scene. First responders, Hazmat crew,& several police agencies arrived on scene. Hazmat crew donned SCBA and started working toward getting the pressure relief valve to close. This step was unsuccessful. They then put some kind of putty in the hole to stop the release. This putty did stop the release of the gas to the atmosphere. The valve was watched to make sure the putty was going to hold. Release lasted approximately 4 hours from the time the driver noticed it until the Hazmat crew was able to plug the valve with the putty. It was discovered the PRV was bent not allow it to close once it popped to release the pressure. Valve was bent due to a baffle that had broke off during transit and hit the PRV bending it.·-
column169: We removed all five trailer's running in this service for our customer to inspect the PRV on each trailer. We changed the schedule 80 stainless steel spray bar to 10 gage stainless steel. We changed the configuration of the baffles to keep them from coming apart and hitting the pressure relief valve. Replaced the BPS pressure relief devices with Marshall pressure relief devices. Set up a procedure to include internal inspection of equipment before closing the trailer.

column162: ATTORNEY FOR DUNCAN OIL TRANSPORTATION SOL.
column168: At approximately 06:33 an explosion related to the vapors in/around tank wagon unit B37, currently being prepared for initial day loading , threw the driver with a transfer hose currently transferring dyed diesel , off the unit. The transfer hose continued  to spray West of the loading rack for approximately 3 minutes , at which time the loaded diesel in compartment #3 had been emptied save for residual product. This meter showed 218.1 gallons transferred through the hose. The impact of the explosion also ruptured welds and bulkheads related to compartment #4 containing approximately 456 gallons of 87E 10 gasoline. During the course of response to the explosion, Springfield FD deployed a 66 gal pop-up containment dike under the leaking #4 compartment. The facility remained inaccessible due to potential fire/safety hazards and it was decided that a pump-off transfer from another tank wagon  vehicle could present additional hazards at the source of explosion had not yet been determined. Instead , a pneumatic pump was deployed to transfer gasoline accumulated in the 66 gal pop up dike to an empty IBC tote already on -site , to prevent it from overflowing , until a vacuum truck with intrinsically sage plumbing capabilities arrived. Clean Harbors arrived with vacuum truck at approximately 15:00 and were able to pump off the remaining gasoline from the tank wagon's compartment # 4, as well as residual diesel from compartment # 2  and #3 and small puddles in the gravel area West of the loading rack area, PCS excavation of impacted area West of the loading rack area was scheduled for approximately noon the following day, 10/9/ based on  expected release time of the scene by on-sight OSHA inspector.
column169: Reinforcement of current training and protocols. Prior to reopening of facility, all drivers were required to be retrained and to be signed off on by supervisor to ensure proper safeguards were in place at all time. Continued training ad monitoring to occur at regularly scheduled intervals.

column168: Vehicle traveling wb on I 26 lost control and collided into guardrail face on the right shoulder. After impact vehicle continued on the guardrail face and overturned. Vehicle caught fire and exploded. Driver injured and taken to hospital.
column169: We are implementing additional training regarding rollovers and distracted driving.  Also we are bringing attention to a dangerous road condition at this section of I-26 The westbound traffic lanes curve to left , The road has superelevation, however there is a 1"-2 dropoff  from the roadway pavement to the right-side shoulder. The right side shoulder is sloped severely away from the travel lanes. This creates a hazardous situation for tractor -trailer drivers if/ when the trailer axle tires drift onto the shoulder / rumble strip. If the right -side trailer tires fall onto the shoulder the slope of the shoulder pulls the trailer further right down. Meanwhile the roadway obligates he driver to travel left along the alignment of the roadway. This situation creates a rollover hazard. the driver now has the tractor traveling  leftward and pitched one direction while the trailer is drifting right and pitched down the opposite direction along the right side shoulder. There have been numerous tractor -trailer accidents in this immediate vicinity, including one just 2 days before this accident : the DOT has enacted a truck speed limit of 55 mph and a sign with an icon of a tipping truck-but a redesign of the roadway should be considered.

FRA INPECTORS COMMENTS AS FOLLOWS: FRA INSPECTION - 10/16/2020- BADGE # 48380 - REPORT NO. 310 CAR-NATX 400147.   SUBJECT TANK CAR DESCRIBED AS UN1075 , RESIDUE : LAST CONTAINED PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED 2.1. WAS IDENTIFIED DURING A HAZMAT INSPECTION RELEASING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0722, IMMEDIATELY AFTER DISCOVERING THE NAR (NON-ACCIDENT RELEASE), I CONTACTED RANDY CAMPBELL, THE ON DUTY TRAINMASTER , AND ALERTED HIM TO THE SITUATION. WE BOTH WENT OUT TO THE CAR AND HE WITNESSED THE CAR LEAKING FROM AROUND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG. HIM TO THE SITUATION. WE BOTH WENT OUT TO THE CAR AND HE WITNESSED THE CAR LEAKING FROM AROUND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG. HE CONTACTED THE CAR DEPARTMENT  TO RESOLVE THE ISSUE.  NO FURTHER INFORMATION WAS AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT.  THE CAR DEPARTMENT TO RESOLVE THE ISSUE. NO FURTHER INFORMATION WAS AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT. THE CAR DEPARTMENT REPORTED THAT NATX 400147 WAS LEAKING BECAUSE THERE WAS NO THREAD SEALANT ON THE PLUG ITSELF , THERE WAS NO ISSUE WITH THE VALVE. THE PLUG WAS REMOVED, THREAD TAPE APPLIED AND THE PLUG WAS REAPPLIED. ALL THE OF THE VALVES, PLUGS AND FITTINGS WERE SPRAYED DOWN AND NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.

column168: On 11/30/2020 at 3:40 PM, a driver who identified a leak during a pre-transportation inspection, reported EMHU 653590 Ieaking in the Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Wiley, TX rail yard. An environmental team was dispatched by the truck operator's employer. KCS Environmental& Hazmat was notified and monitored response activities. Upon arrival, responders determined that approximately 10 gallons was released from a 275 gallon IBC Tote. The tote was found with an unsecured closure on top of the tote. The closure was secured, and EMHU 65359 was unloaded so the spill could be neutralized and remediated. The small amount that leaked outside of the container was cleaned. Upon completion, the contents were reloaded and properly blocked and braced. The container was subsequently outgated. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating On several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar. com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On 11/29/2020 at 7:45AM, the Kansas City Southern Railway's train, MBMSH-29, derailed in Mauriceville, TX. Twenty five rail cars derailed, including four hazmat tank cars of note. Two of the hazmat tank cars, UTLX 647575 and UTLX, 647138, containing ETHANOLAMINE (UN2491), Class 8, PGIII) released a total of 33,789 gallons a result of damage incurred from the derailment . Specifically, UTLX 647575 released 13,770 gallons from a hole in the bottom outlet valve , which opened and it's handle sheared off during the derailment.  An evacuation was ordered due to the derailment of two of the other hazmat tank cars., UTLX 900859 and UTLX 930521, were re-railed, and moved per 49CFR 174.5 to a safe location for further attention. Approximately 1,000 people were initially evacuated for the first 24 hours. This number was reduced to about 50 individuals for the next 24 hours.  Then this was reduced to 7 people , for an additional 5 days.  The road FM 1130, adjacent to the derailment was closed for 5 days.  File note: Item 19- the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing.  This shipment was offered as a bulk shipment , aka  one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier.  The carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantity this valve.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON UNLOADS WET. PUT INTO HAZMAT BAG LINED TOTE. DescribePack: PACKAGE HAD FOUR BOTTLES OF ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL THAT HAD LOOSE CAPS THAT LEAKED. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED UPRIGHT INSIDE A TOTE.

SequenceEvent: Package was being transported to van when a manager noticed there was liquid on the bottom of drum.  Package was taken to hazmat cage in a hazmat tub. DescribePack: There is a small leak on the bottom rim of the drum that appears to be pinhole size or less. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Drum was turned upside down which stopped the material from leaking.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: SequenceEvent: package found in unloads at roughly 0200 on 10-2. inspection found two of four bottles leaked resulting in damage/contamination of other contents. DescribePack: defective threaded caps that leaked on two bottles despite being tightened down.  can see when observing bottles that two were obviously at a lower level than the others. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: absorbent material used to clean up liquid spill; package placed in a bag and tote until processing.

SequenceEvent: shipment was taken out of system flow due to external carton wet and leaking. package came off trailer #812144 already damaged wet and leaking, upon inspection of inner contents 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of key supra lp machine warewashing detergent. one 1 gallon plastic bottle had a loose cap allowing .15 gallons to release. no slotted partitions bags or absorbent was found.  facility procedures for damaged hazardous materials followed contents contained and awaiting disposition. DescribePack: 1 of 4 one gallon plastic bottle had a loose cap allowing .15 gallons to release. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: leaking package was placed in a hazmat bag lined tote.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS FOUND ONTHE UNLOAD SIDE WITH A WET BOTTOM AND IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO THE HAZMAT AREA. DescribePack: INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE CAP ON ONE OF THE GALLON BOTTLES HAD CRACKED AND CAME OFF ALLOWING SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO AN AREA WHERE IT WOULD NOT BE HANDLED.

SequenceEvent: Package found on load ends at 17:45 on 10-5. package was wet from internal leakage; one bottle of quat-stat 5 leaked and contaminated the rest of the contents with corrosive material DescribePack: one cap was cross threaded / loose and leakage resulted. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package was contained in a bag and tote using gloves; packaging absorbed material spill

SequenceEvent: Package must have been tipped on its side at some point to allow the loose cap to start leaking.  package brought to QA for inspection and found that it was leaking from the inside out. DescribePack: Cap was on loose and crooked on one of the bottles. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: placed and sealed in salvage drum

SequenceEvent: The Package was found and immediately sequestered. any leakage from the Hazmat occurred internally. The hazmat was placed in drum for inspection. DescribePack: Package failure occurred at the caps, two 1 gallon jugs were leaking through the caps because the caps were not on tight enough. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Box was immediately placed in a drum and inspected.
